The `static` keyword in programming has different meanings depending on the context in which it's used. Here are a few common uses of `static`:

1. **Static Variables**: In a class, a variable declared as `static` belongs to the class itself, not to any instance of the class. This means there's only one copy of the variable, shared by all instances of the class.

   ```java
public class MyClass {
    public static int myStaticVariable = 10;
}
```

   In this example, `myStaticVariable` is a class variable, and you can access it using the class name.

   ```java
MyClass.myStaticVariable = 20;
```

2. **Static Methods**: A method declared as `static` can be called without creating an instance of the class. It belongs to the class itself, not to any instance of the class.

   ```java
public class MyClass {
    public static void myStaticMethod() {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}
```

